@node Starting "Getting Started"

@{fg shine} From the Startup-Sequence@{fg text}

 Put AddNH into the C drawer, of the floppy disk or hard drive you are going
 to boot with. To run AddNH simply re-boot your amiga. If you try and boot
 from a floppy drive when you have an hard drive the hard drive will have
 priority over the floppy drive. If you only have floppy drives or only have
 a hard drive then AddNH will boot as normal.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From CLI@{fg text}

 Put AddNH anywhere you please. In your C drawer, Tools drawer or whereever.
 Start a CLI Process (I.e. use CLI, Shell or Workbench's `Execute' menu) and
 type the pathname for AddNH (I.e WORK:Tools/AddNH, AddNH, etc) and then
 press ENTER. This will run AddNH. Alternatively. Type the pathname for
 AddNH followed by one or more CLI Arguments and then press ENTER.

 @{" CLI Arguments " Link "Arguments"}

@{fg shine} From Workbench@{fg text}

 Make sure there is a TOOL Icon on AddNH and then double-click on AddNH.
 This will run AddNH, which will then read the TOOL Icon for AddNH ToolTypes
 If it finds any it will set the appropriate values inside AddNH.

 @{" ToolTypes    " Link "ToolTypes"}
@endnode

@node Arguments "CLI Arguments"

@{fg fill} Below is a list of AddNH CLI Keywords with their Arguments. AddNH will not
 interpret an argument if its keyword is missing. I.e You cannot just type
 the argument -32 without typing the keyword HANDLERPRIORITY for example as
 other keywords might use a -32 argument. Thus, AddNH would have an hard
 time differentiating everything.

 You can use more than one keyword/argument set. Example:

 AddNH SETGAMEPORT MOUSEINJPORT SETBORDER BORDERON HANDLERPRIORITY -32

 Keywords and Arguments must be UPPERCASE. As a result of you Typing in
 uppercase AddNH does not get clogged up with conversion code, opening of
 the Utility.Library, etc.

@{fg shine} CLI Arguments@{fg text}

 SETGAMEPORT MOUSEINMPORT/MOUSEINJPORT

 This allows you to choose which GamePort the mouse uses. MOUSEINJPORT means
 the mouse will operate from the Joystick Port. MOUSEINMPORT means the mouse
 will operate from the Mouse Port


 SETCONTROLLER NOCONTROLLER/MOUSE/RELATIVEJOYSTICK/ABSOLUTEJOYSTICK

 This allows you to choose what type of Controller to use as a mouse.
 NOCONTROLLER means you want the mouse's port declared as empty. This could
 be of use to your Startup-Sequence if you do not want the user to be using
 the mouse upon startup for example. MOUSE means you want to use a mouse in
 the mouse's port. RELATIVEJOYSTICK means you want to use a relative
 joystick in the mouse's port. ABSOLUTEJOYSTICK means you want to use an
 absolute joystick in the mouse's port.


 SETBORDER BORDEROFF/BORDERON

 This allows you to choose wether or not to have a Border around your
 screen. BORDEROFF means you switch off (remove) the border. BORDERON
 means you switch on (use) the border.


 HANDLERPRIORITY Priority

 The priority can be -32, -16, 0, 16 or 32 (The allowed values of a software
 interrupt). However. I have used a default value of 100. 100 is the value
 used in the RKM example code for this kind of Handler.
@{fg fill}
 Default values are used when a Keyword/Argument is not used/entered.@{fg fill}
@endnode

