@node Keys "Handler Keys"
@{fg shine}
 Extra Keys@{fg text}

 The idea behind using the following NumericPad Keys as extra (spare) keys
 is to limit wear/tear of the normal keys they emulate.

  8  2  4  6   Have become Cursor Keys. Use R-Shift to emulate Page-Up, etc.

           5   Has become SPACE BAR.

           7   Has become HELP.

           .   Has become DELETE.

       Enter   Has become RETURN
@{fg fill}
 The Handler stays active until you either remove it with the RemoveNH
 program (after pressing CONTROL 0 from within FunctionKeysNH, if you
 activated FunctionKeysNH) or you remove it by sending its Message Port
 a PMCOMMAND_QUIT instruction (after any other PMCOMMANDs have finished).
@endnode

@node Funcs "Handler Functions"
@{fg shine}
 Handler Functions@{fg text}

 The idea behind using the following NumericPad Keys for certain functions
 is so that you have those functions at the touch of two buttons instead of
 having to programme or CLI them yourself.

 R.AMIGA (      Switch Off the clicking sound of DF0:
 
 CONTROL (      Switch On the clicking sound of DF0:

 R.AMIGA )      Switch Off the clicking sound of DF1:
 
 CONTROL )      Switch On the clicking sound of DF1:

 R.AMIGA /      Switch Off the clicking sound of DF2:
 
 CONTROL /      Switch On the clicking sound of DF2:

 R.AMIGA *      Switch Off the clicking sound of DF3:
 
 CONTROL *      Switch On the clicking sound of DF3:

 R.AMIGA -      Switch Off the Border.
 
 CONTROL -      Switch On the Border.

 R.AMIGA +      The Mouse will operate from the Joystick Port.
 
 CONTROL +      The Mouse will operate from the Mouse Port.

 CONTROL 7      The Mouse Pointer will be operated by no controller at all.

 CONTROL 9      The Mouse Pointer will be operated by a Mouse.

 CONTROL 3      The Mouse Pointer will be operated by a Relative Joystick.

 CONTROL 1      The Mouse Pointer will be operated by an Absolute Joystick.

 R.AMIGA 0      Reset the Amiga.
 
 CONTROL 0      Switch Off NumericPad functions.
@{fg fill}
 The above keys are only available when you either use the FunctionKeysNH
 program or you send the handler's Message Port a PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD
 instruction. The PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD instruction sends the handler into
 a `monitor-the-keyboard' loop. When it is in this loop the amiga will
 become a bit slower. When you stop the loop, by pressing CONTROL 0, the
 amiga will return to its previous speed. Really you should: go into the
 loop with the FunctionKeysNH program, de/activate the function/s you need
 and then press CONTROL 0. I.e The handler should really be meant for the
 Handler Keys and not as a full-time keyboard monitor.
@endnode

@node HPort "Handler Port"
@{fg shine}
 Handler Port@{fg text}

 The Handler Port can receive Port Messages (See `Missing_Keys.i'). Apart
 from the other PMCOMMANDS_ instructions in the include file, there are
 (at the moment) only two important PMCOMMANDS_ instructions the port can
 receive. PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD and PMCOMMAND_GETSTATUS.

 PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD puts AddNH into a `monitor-the-keyboard' loop.
 The amiga will become a bit slower when this happens because AddNH is not
 sleeping - WaitPort() - until you press CONTROL 0. When you do press
 CONTROL 0 AddNH is put to sleep. pm_Status then has the value of 255, but
 cannot be returned as AddNH is sleeping. PMCOMMAND_GETSTATUS is used to
 get the pm_Status value. As you are sending a message (PMCOMMAND_GETSTATUS)
 AddNH can reply with the 255 pm_Status value.

 You MUST use PMCOMMAND_GETSTATUS after PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD because even
 if you know the `monitor-the-keyboard' loop has finished how would you know
 if some other program has not re-issued a PMCOMMAND_USENUMERICPAD.
@endnode

